paper_tex_content.Method:
The TCDP method is composed of two major stages: forward diffusion and reverse purification. In the forward stage, adversarial inputs are progressively corrupted with noise according to an adaptive schedule informed by insights from Tweedie’s theory. This controlled noise addition helps dilute the adversarial signal.

In the reverse stage, a denoising network is applied in two consecutive passes. The first pass, using a denoiser D1, removes the bulk of the noise and computes a consistency loss defined as the mean squared error between the noisy input and the output of D1. The second pass employs a second denoiser D2 to refine the output and ensure that small deviations in noise do not result in abrupt changes in the final output. Training is performed using a double application of Tweedie’s formula: the first application addresses the denoising requirement at the original noise level, while the second enforces consistency across adjacent noise levels. The adaptive noise control mechanism is implemented to reduce unnecessary computational overhead while maintaining purification quality.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\State Initialize input x \(\leftarrow\) adversarial sample
\State Set step counter t \(\leftarrow 0\) and define maximum steps T
\While{t \(<\) T}
    \State Compute intermediate output: \(\hat{x} \leftarrow D1(x)\)
    \State Calculate consistency loss: \(\ell \leftarrow ||\hat{x} - x||^2 \)
    \If{\(\ell < \) threshold}
        \State \textbf{break}
    \Else
        \State Update x using D2: \(x \leftarrow D2(\hat{x})\)
    \EndIf
    \State Increment t \(\leftarrow t + 1\)
\EndWhile
\end{algorithmic}
\caption{Reverse Diffusion Process with Adaptive Noise Control}
\end{algorithm}

paper_tex_content.Results:
Experimental results show that TCDP enhances purification performance under adversarial attacks. In Experiment 1, as PGD epsilon increases, TCDP achieves lower reconstruction error (mean MSE around 0.2357) compared to Purify++ (mean MSE of approximately 0.2706), with corresponding improvements in classification accuracy. Figure~[H] illustrates the trend in classification accuracy versus PGD epsilon.

\begin{figure}[H]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{images/classification_plot.pdf}
  \caption{Classification Accuracy vs. PGD Epsilon}
\end{figure}

In the ablation study (Experiment 2), the full TCDP configuration consistently outperforms both the no-consistency and fixed noise variants, confirming the importance of the double Tweedie approach and adaptive noise control. Experiment 3 demonstrates that the adaptive module typically requires only one reverse diffusion step with an average execution time per batch of approximately 0.0102 seconds, achieving an effective balance between computational efficiency and purification quality. Detailed plots and tables (saved as PDF files in the images directory) further substantiate these findings.

